VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
REASON: Both drifts reproduce on HEAD. D1: src/smp_state.rs:360-378 stop_cpu_decide takes only active_cpus (no cpu_id); its Verus ensures only constrains the count, so stop_cpu_decide(2) returns Ok(1) and the PoC assertion fires — the header (line 29) and SM3 claim "CPU 0 never stops" is not proved. The companion lemma_cpu0_never_stops (306-309) is vacuous (assumes active==1, proves !(active>1), never mentions cpu id). The C shim gale_smp_cpu_stop_checked(int id) at zephyr/gale_smp_state.c:54-73 accepts id and drops it. D2: the model's global_lock_count is a single u32 on SmpState, but upstream zephyr/kernel/smp.c:57-83 stores the counter per-thread (_current->base.global_lock_count), arbitrates via atomic_cas on a separate global_lock, and restores interrupt state via arch_irq_unlock(key) — the model has neither the atomic nor the irq key. SM4's lemma_lock_unlock_roundtrip is internally sound on a fabricated object. Not a documented caller-responsibility issue; SMP is in gale's declared scope; STPA-GAP-2 audit already flags gale_smp_*_decide RED (docs/safety/stpa-gap2-audit.md:294-297) but for a weaker reason ("no model call") than the identity/abstraction drift shown here. No UCA to map to: artifacts/stpa.yaml explicitly scopes out UCAs ("Control structure, UCAs, and loss scenarios are out of scope for this initial artifact"), and no safety/stpa/ucas.yaml exists. Recommend filing two new UCAs under a future SMP grouping — SMP-UCA-3 (stop_cpu accepted with cpu_id==0 while active_cpus>1; H-like SMP availability hazard feeding L-3) and SMP-UCA-4 (global_lock/unlock claim SM4 verification while modeling a different object than z_smp_global_lock; feeds L-2).
